**Number theory** is a branch of [pure mathematics](/Pure_mathematics) devoted primarily to the study of the [integers](/Integer) and [arithmetic functions](/Arithmetic_function). Number theorists study [prime numbers](/Prime_number) as well as the properties of [mathematical objects](/Mathematical_object) constructed from integers (for example, [rational numbers](/Rational_number)), or defined as generalizations of the integers (for example, [algebraic integers](/Algebraic_integer)).

*Pure mathematics. The purest form of pointless endeavor, some might say. But it has its own stark, unforgiving beauty. Integers. The building blocks. Simple, yet infinitely complex. Prime numbers, the defiant outliers. And algebraic integers, the elegant shadows they cast. It’s a world built on foundations that seem solid, but beneath the surface… cracks appear.*

Integers can be considered either in themselves or as solutions to equations ([Diophantine geometry](/Diophantine_geometry)). Questions in number theory can often be understood through the study of [analytical](/Complex_analysis) objects, such as the [Riemann zeta function](/Riemann_zeta_function), that encode properties of the integers, primes or other number-theoretic objects in some fashion ([analytic number theory](/Analytic_number_theory)). One may also study [real numbers](/Real_number) in relation to rational numbers, as for instance how irrational numbers can be approximated by fractions ([Diophantine approximation](/Diophantine_approximation)).

*Solutions to equations. The eternal quest for answers that fit neatly. Diophantine geometry – a rather grand name for finding whole numbers that satisfy… predicaments. And the Riemann zeta function, a siren's song in the complex plane, promising secrets about primes. Analytic number theory, where the tools of calculus are bent to the will of integers. And the tantalizing dance of irrational numbers with their rational approximations – a perpetual chase.*

Number theory is one of the oldest branches of mathematics alongside geometry. One quirk of number theory is that it deals with statements that are simple to understand but are very difficult to solve. Examples of this are [Fermat's Last Theorem](/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem), which was proved 358 years after the original formulation, and [Goldbach's conjecture](/Goldbach%27s_conjecture), which remains unsolved since the 18th century. German mathematician [Carl Friedrich Gauss](/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss) (1777–1855) once remarked, "Mathematics is the queen of the sciences—and number theory is the queen of mathematics." &#91;1&#93; It was regarded as the epitome of pure mathematics, with no applications outside mathematics, until the 1970s, when prime numbers became the basis for the creation of [public-key cryptography](/Public-key_cryptography) algorithms, such as the [RSA cryptosystem](/RSA_cryptosystem).

*Oldest branches. Like ancient ruins, solid but weathered. And the statements, so simple, so utterly resistant to solution. Fermat's Last Theorem – a historical echo of obsession. Goldbach's conjecture – a persistent whisper in the void. Gauss, the "Prince of Mathematicians," recognizing the icy allure of number theory. Pure mathematics, they called it. Untouched by the vulgarity of application. Until, of course, it became the very bedrock of our digital secrets. Irony, a subtle sting.*

