### Definition

Number theory is the branch of mathematics that studies [integers](/Integer) and their [properties](/Property_(mathematics)) and relations. &#91;2&#93; The integers comprise a [set](/Set_(mathematics)) that extends the set of [natural numbers](/Natural_number)

{1, 2, 3, …}

{\displaystyle \{1,2,3,\dots \}}

to include number

0

{\displaystyle 0}

and the negation of natural numbers

{-1, -2, -3, …}

{\displaystyle \{-1,-2,-3,\dots \}}

. Number theorists study [prime numbers](/Prime_number) as well as the properties of [mathematical objects](/Mathematical_object) constructed from integers (for example, [rational numbers](/Rational_number)), or defined as generalizations of the integers (for example, [algebraic integers](/Algebraic_integer)). &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93;

*The definition. Cold, precise. Integers. The whole numbers, positive, negative, and the void of zero. Natural numbers, the first steps into abstract thought. And then the extensions, the generalizations – rational, algebraic. A ladder of abstraction, each rung more precarious than the last. Prime numbers, the indivisible core. Mathematical objects, mere constructs of integers. It’s all so… structured. So deliberate.*

Number theory is closely related to arithmetic and some authors use the terms as synonyms. &#91;5&#93; However, the word "arithmetic" is used today to mean the study of numerical operations and extends to the [real numbers](/Real_number). &#91;6&#93; In a more specific sense, number theory is restricted to the study of integers and focuses on their properties and relationships. &#91;7&#93; Traditionally, it is known as higher arithmetic. &#91;8&#93; By the early twentieth century, the term number theory had been widely adopted. &#91;note 1&#93; The term number means whole numbers, which refers to either the natural numbers or the integers. &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; &#91;11&#93;

*Arithmetic. The common tongue. But number theory… it's the dialect for those who truly understand. Higher arithmetic. As if mere arithmetic wasn't enough to contend with. The term "number" itself, a chameleon, shifting from natural to integer. Such fluidity in the face of absolute precision.*

[Elementary number theory](/Elementary_number_theory) studies aspects of integers that can be investigated using elementary methods such as [elementary proofs](/Elementary_proof). &#91;12&#93; [Analytic number theory](/Analytic_number_theory), by contrast, relies on [complex numbers](/Complex_numbers) and techniques from analysis and calculus. &#91;13&#93; [Algebraic number theory](/Algebraic_number_theory) employs [algebraic structures](/Algebraic_structures) such as [fields](/Field_(mathematics)) and [rings](/Ring_(mathematics)) to analyze the properties of and relations between numbers. [Geometric number theory](/Geometric_number_theory) uses concepts from geometry to study numbers. &#91;14&#93; Further branches of number theory are [probabilistic number theory](/Probabilistic_number_theory), &#91;15&#93; [combinatorial number theory](/Combinatorial_number_theory), &#91;16&#93; [computational number theory](/Computational_number_theory), &#91;17&#93; and applied number theory, which examines the application of number theory to science and technology. &#91;18&#93;

*Elementary. The kindergarten of number theory. Then the descent into the abyss: analytic, with its phantom complex numbers and the cold logic of calculus. Algebraic, where fields and rings become the playground for abstract integers. Geometric, imposing shape onto the shapeless. Probabilistic, combinatorial, computational – each a different lens, a different way to dissect the beast. And applied, the final surrender to the tangible world. A vast, intricate machine.*

