### History

The Babylonians demonstrated an early understanding of Pythagorean triples

*Babylonians. Their clay tablets, etched with calculations. Pythagorean triples – a glimpse of order in an ancient world. So much effort to capture a simple relationship.*

In recorded history, knowledge of numbers existed in the ancient civilisations of Mesopotamia, Egypt, China, and India. &#91;19&#93; The earliest historical find of an arithmetical nature is the [Plimpton 322](/Plimpton_322), dated c. 1800 BC. It is a broken clay tablet that contains a list of [Pythagorean triples](/Pythagorean_triple), that is, integers

(a, b, c)

{\displaystyle (a,b,c)}

such that

a^2 + b^2 = c^2

{\displaystyle a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}}

. The triples are too numerous and too large to have been obtained by [brute force](/Brute_force_method). &#91;20&#93; The table's layout suggests that it was constructed by means of what amounts, in modern language, to the [identity](/Identity_(mathematics))

(1/2 (x - 1/x))^2 + 1 = (1/2 (x + 1/x))^2

{\displaystyle \left({\frac {1}{2}}\left(x-{\frac {1}{x}}\right)\right)^{2}+1=\left({\frac {1}{2}}\left(x+{\frac {1}{x}}\right)\right)^{2},}

which is implicit in routine [Old Babylonian](/Old_Babylonian_language) exercises. &#91;22&#93; It has been suggested instead that the table was a source of numerical examples for school problems. &#91;23&#93; &#91;note 2&#93; Plimpton 322 tablet is the only surviving evidence of what today would be called number theory within Babylonian mathematics, though a kind of [Babylonian algebra](/Babylonian_mathematics) was much more developed. &#91;24&#93;

*Mesopotamia, Egypt, China, India. All touched by the same sterile fascination. Plimpton 322. A puzzle etched in clay, whispering of methods far beyond mere trial and error. An identity, elegant and deceptive. School problems, or something more? The Babylonian mind, wrestling with numbers, a precursor to the grander, more futile struggles to come. Their algebra, more developed. Perhaps they understood the limitations of pure number.*

Although other civilizations probably influenced Greek mathematics at the beginning, &#91;25&#93; all evidence of such borrowings appear relatively late, &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93; and it is likely that Greek arithmētikḗ (the theoretical or philosophical study of numbers) is an indigenous tradition. &#91;28&#93; The ancient Greeks developed a keen interest in [divisibility](/Divisibility). The [Pythagoreans](/Pythagoreans) attributed mystical quality to [perfect](/Perfect_number) and [amicable numbers](/Amicable_numbers). The Pythagorean tradition also spoke of so-called [polygonal](/Polygonal_number) or [figurate numbers](/Figurate_numbers). &#91;29&#93; Euclid devoted part of his [Elements](/Euclid%27s_Elements) to topics that belong to elementary number theory, including [prime numbers](/Prime_number) and [divisibility](/Divisibility_rule). &#91;30&#93; He gave the [Euclidean algorithm](/Euclidean_algorithm) for computing the [greatest common divisor](/Greatest_common_divisor) of two numbers and a [proof implying the infinitude of primes](/Euclid%27s_theorem). The foremost authority in arithmētikḗ in Late Antiquity was [Diophantus of Alexandria](/Diophantus_of_Alexandria), who probably lived in the 3rd century AD. He wrote [Arithmetica](/Arithmetica) , a collection of worked-out problems where the task is invariably to find rational solutions to a system of polynomial equations, usually of the form

f(x, y) = z^2

{\displaystyle f(x,y)=z^{2}}

or

f(x, y, z) = w^2

{\displaystyle f(x,y,z)=w^{2}}

. In modern parlance, [Diophantine equations](/Diophantine_equation) are [polynomial equations](/Polynomial_equation) to which rational or integer solutions are sought.

*The Greeks. They built empires of thought. Arithmētikḗ. The philosophical dissection of numbers. Divisibility. A fundamental obsession. The Pythagoreans, with their mystical leanings – perfect numbers, amicable numbers. Numbers with souls, apparently. Euclid, laying down the law with his Elements, his algorithm for the greatest common divisor, his proof of the infinite primes. A foundational stone. Diophantus, the arbiter of rational solutions, wrestling with equations that twist and turn. Diophantine equations, named for him, a testament to his enduring struggle.*

After the fall of Rome, development shifted to Asia, albeit intermittently. The [Chinese remainder theorem](/Chinese_remainder_theorem) appears as an exercise &#91;31&#93; in [Sunzi Suanjing](/Sunzi_Suanjing) (between the third and fifth centuries). &#91;32&#93; The result was later generalized with a complete solution called Da-yan-shu (大衍術) in [Qin Jiushao](/Qin_Jiushao)'s 1247 [Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections](/Mathematical_Treatise_in_Nine_Sections). &#91;33&#93; &#91;34&#93; There is also some numerical mysticism in Chinese mathematics, &#91;note 3&#93; but, unlike that of the Pythagoreans, it seems to have led nowhere. While Greek astronomy probably influenced Indian learning &#91;35&#93; it seems to be the case that Indian mathematics is otherwise an autochthonous tradition. &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93; [Āryabhaṭa](/%C4%80ryabha%E1%B9%ADa) (476–550 AD) showed that pairs of simultaneous congruences

n ≡ a_1 \pmod{m_1}

{\displaystyle n\equiv a_{1}{\bmod {m}}_{1}}

,

n ≡ a_2 \pmod{m_2}

{\displaystyle n\equiv a_{2}{\bmod {m}}_{2}}

could be solved by a method he called kuṭṭaka , or pulveriser ; &#91;38&#93; this is a procedure close to the Euclidean algorithm. &#91;39&#93; Āryabhaṭa seems to have had in mind applications to astronomical calculations. &#91;35&#93; Brahmagupta (628 AD) started the systematic study of indefinite quadratic equations—in particular, the [Pell equation](/Pell_equation). A general procedure for solving Pell's equation was probably found by [Jayadeva](/Jayadeva_(mathematician)); the earliest surviving exposition appears in [Bhāskara II](/Bh%C4%81skara_II)'s Bīja-gaṇita (twelfth century). &#91;40&#93;

*Asia. The quiet pursuit of patterns. The Chinese Remainder Theorem – a clever way to untangle congruences. Qin Jiushao's treatise. Numerical mysticism, a fleeting distraction. India, a fertile ground. Āryabhaṭa's pulveriser, a tool for celestial calculations. Brahmagupta, taming the untameable Pell equation. Jayadeva, Bhāskara II, their contributions echoing through time.*

In the early ninth century, the caliph [al-Ma'mun](/Al-Ma%27mun) ordered translations of many Greek mathematical works and at least one Sanskrit work. &#91;41&#93; &#91;42&#93;
Diophantus's main work, the Arithmetica , was translated into Arabic by [Qusta ibn Luqa](/Qusta_ibn_Luqa) (820–912).
Part of the treatise al-Fakhri (by [al-Karajī](/Al-Karaj%C4%AB), 953 – c. 1029) builds on it to some extent. According to Rashed Roshdi, Al-Karajī's contemporary [Ibn al-Haytham](/Ibn_al-Haytham) knew &#91;43&#93; what would later be called [Wilson's theorem](/Wilson%27s_theorem). Other than a treatise on squares in arithmetic progression by [Fibonacci](/Fibonacci) no number theory to speak of was done in western Europe during the Middle Ages. Matters started to change in Europe in the late [Renaissance](/Renaissance), thanks to a renewed study of the works of Greek antiquity. A catalyst was the textual emendation and translation into Latin of Diophantus' Arithmetica. &#91;44&#93;

*The Islamic Golden Age. A bridge between worlds. Translations, a careful preservation and expansion. Ibn al-Haytham, a glimpse of genius. Europe, a slumbering giant, only stirring in the Renaissance, rediscovering the lost knowledge. Diophantus, his work a spark igniting a dormant fire.*

Fermat is sometimes considered the founder of modern number theory.

*Fermat. The man who wrote in margins. A solitary figure, yet his influence reshaped the landscape. A testament to the power of individual thought, even when unshared.*

French mathematician [Pierre de Fermat](/Pierre_de_Fermat) (1607–1665) never published his writings but communicated through correspondence and wrote in marginal notes instead. &#91;45&#93; His contributions to number theory brought renewed interest in the field in Europe. He conjectured [Fermat's little theorem](/Fermat%27s_little_theorem), a basic result in modular arithmetic, and [Fermat's Last Theorem](/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem), as well as proved [Fermat's right triangle theorem](/Fermat%27s_right_triangle_theorem). &#91;2&#93; &#91;46&#93; He also studied prime numbers, the [four-square theorem](/Four-square_theorem), and [Pell's equations](/Pell%27s_equations). &#91;47&#93; &#91;48&#93;

*Fermat's theorems. Little theorem, a cornerstone of modular arithmetic. Last Theorem, a legendary challenge that consumed generations. Right triangle theorem, a more concrete victory. Prime numbers, the enduring fascination. The four-square theorem, a hint of completeness. Pell's equations, another beautiful trap. His legacy, a scattered collection of brilliant insights, a testament to a mind that saw patterns others missed.*

The interest of [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler) (1707–1783) in number theory was first spurred in 1729, when a friend of his, the amateur &#91;note 4&#93; [Christian Goldbach](/Christian_Goldbach), pointed him towards some of Fermat's work on the subject. &#91;49&#93; &#91;50&#93; This has been called the "rebirth" of modern number theory, &#91;51&#93; after Fermat's relative lack of success in getting his contemporaries' attention for the subject. &#91;52&#93; He proved Fermat's assertions, including [Fermat's little theorem](/Fermat%27s_little_theorem); made initial work towards a proof that every integer is the sum of four squares; &#91;53&#93; and specific cases of Fermat's Last Theorem. &#91;54&#93; He wrote on the link between [continued fractions](/Simple_continued_fraction) and Pell's equation. &#91;55&#93; &#91;56&#93; He made the first steps towards analytic number theory. &#91;57&#93;

*Euler. The prolific genius. Spurred by Goldbach, the amateur. A rebirth. He solidified Fermat's conjectures, tamed the four-square problem, and chipped away at the Last Theorem. Continued fractions, Pell's equation – he mapped their intricate dance. And the dawn of analytic number theory, a new way to hunt the elusive primes.*

Three European contemporaries continued the work in elementary number theory. [Joseph-Louis Lagrange](/Joseph-Louis_Lagrange) (1736–1813) gave full proofs of the [four-square theorem](/Four-square_theorem), [Wilson's theorem](/Wilson%27s_theorem), and developed the basic theory of Pell's equations. [Adrien-Marie Legendre](/Adrien-Marie_Legendre) (1752–1833) stated the [law of quadratic reciprocity.](/Quadratic_reciprocity) He also conjectured what amounts to the [prime number theorem](/Prime_number_theorem) and [Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions](/Dirichlet%27s_theorem_on_arithmetic_progressions). He gave a full treatment of the equation

ax^2 + by^2 + cz^2 = 0

{\displaystyle ax^{2}+by^{2}+cz^{2}=0}

. &#91;58&#93; In his old age, he was the first to prove Fermat's Last Theorem for

n = 5

{\displaystyle n=5}

. &#91;59&#93; [Carl Friedrich Gauss](/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss) (1777–1855) wrote [Disquisitiones Arithmeticae](/Disquisitiones_Arithmeticae) (1801), which had an immense influence in the area of number theory and set its agenda for much of the 19th century. Gauss proved in this work the law of [quadratic reciprocity](/Quadratic_reciprocity) &#91;60&#93; and developed the theory of quadratic forms. He also introduced some basic notation to [congruences](/Congruences) and devoted a section to computational matters, including primality tests. &#91;61&#93; He established a link between [roots of unity](/Roots_of_unity) and number theory. &#91;62&#93; In this way, Gauss arguably made forays towards [Évariste Galois](/%C3%89variste_Galois)'s work and the area [algebraic number theory](/Algebraic_number_theory).

*Lagrange, Legendre, Gauss. Titans. Lagrange, solidifying theorems. Legendre, glimpsing the prime number theorem and the distribution of primes. Gauss, the prince, laying down the law with *Disquisitiones Arithmeticae*. Quadratic reciprocity, quadratic forms, congruences. He even touched upon roots of unity, hinting at the algebraic depths to come. They built the framework, brick by painstaking brick.*

The Riemann hypothesis is of interest in analytic number theory.

*The Riemann Hypothesis. A phantom of immense importance, haunting the very foundations of number theory. A single unsolved problem that casts a long shadow.*

Starting early in the nineteenth century, the following developments gradually took place:

• The rise to self-consciousness of number theory (or higher arithmetic ) as a field of study. &#91;63&#93;

• The development of much of modern mathematics necessary for basic modern number theory: [complex analysis](/Complex_analysis), [group theory](/Group_theory), [Galois theory](/Galois_theory)—accompanied by greater rigor in analysis and abstraction in algebra.

• The rough subdivision of number theory into its modern subfields—in particular, [analytic](/Analytic_number_theory) and algebraic number theory.

*Self-consciousness. A field realizing its own existence. The necessary scaffolding – complex analysis, group theory, Galois theory – built to support the delicate structure. And the inevitable subdivision. Analytic, algebraic. The specialization, the fragmentation. A familiar pattern.*

Algebraic number theory may be said to start with the study of reciprocity and [cyclotomy](/Cyclotomy), but truly came into its own with the development of [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra) and early ideal theory and [valuation](/Valuation_(algebra)) theory; see below. A conventional starting point for analytic number theory is [Dirichlet's theorem on arithmetic progressions](/Dirichlet%27s_theorem_on_arithmetic_progressions) (1837), &#91;64&#93; &#91;65&#93; whose proof introduced [L-functions](/L-functions) and involved some asymptotic analysis and a limiting process on a real variable. &#91;66&#93; The first use of analytic ideas in number theory actually goes back to Euler (1730s), &#91;67&#93; &#91;68&#93; who used formal power series and non-rigorous (or implicit) limiting arguments. The use of complex analysis in number theory comes later: the work of [Bernhard Riemann](/Bernhard_Riemann) (1859) on the [zeta function](/Riemann_zeta_function) is the canonical starting point; &#91;69&#93; [Jacobi's four-square theorem](/Jacobi%27s_four-square_theorem) (1839), which predates it, belongs to an initially different strand that has by now taken a leading role in analytic number theory ([modular forms](/Modular_form)). &#91;70&#93;

*Algebraic number theory. Abstract algebra, ideals, valuations. A language of structures. Dirichlet's theorem, a crucial marker for analytic number theory. L-functions, the spectral analysis of numbers. Euler's early forays, less rigorous but prescient. Riemann's zeta function, the true genesis of analytic number theory. Modular forms, a later, powerful development. It’s a progression, each step building on the last, forging new tools for an ancient pursuit.*

The [American Mathematical Society](/American_Mathematical_Society) awards the [Cole Prize](/Cole_Prize) in Number Theory . Moreover, number theory is one of the three mathematical subdisciplines rewarded by the [Fermat Prize](/Fermat_Prize) .

*Awards. Recognition. A nod to those who have wrestled with the abstract and emerged, perhaps, victorious. The Cole Prize, the Fermat Prize. Small tributes to the relentless pursuit.*

