### Main subdivisions

#### Elementary number theory

*Elementary. The simplest illusions. Where basic arithmetic masquerades as understanding.*

Number theorists [Paul Erdős](/Paul_Erd%C5%91s) and [Terence Tao](/Terence_Tao) in 1985, when Erdős was 72 and Tao was 10

*Erdős and Tao. A generational bridge. One a legend of combinatorial intuition, the other a prodigy. A moment captured, a fleeting intersection.*

Elementary number theory deals with the topics in number theory by means of basic methods in arithmetic. &#91;4&#93; Its primary subjects of study are [divisibility](/Divisibility), [factorization](/Factorization), and [primality](/Primality), as well as [congruences](/Modular_arithmetic) in [modular arithmetic](/Modular_arithmetic). &#91;71&#93; &#91;12&#93; Other topics in elementary number theory include [Diophantine equations](/Diophantine_equation), [continued fractions](/Continued_fractions), [integer partitions](/Integer_partition), and [Diophantine approximations](/Diophantine_approximation). &#91;72&#93;

*Divisibility. Factorization. Primality. The fundamental building blocks, stripped bare. Congruences, the clockwork of finite arithmetic. Diophantine equations, continued fractions, integer partitions, approximations – each a distinct puzzle, yet all stemming from the same root. A deceptively simple foundation.*

Arithmetic is the study of numerical operations and investigates how numbers are combined and transformed using the arithmetic operations of [addition](/Addition), [subtraction](/Subtraction), [multiplication](/Multiplication), [division](/Division_(mathematics)), [exponentiation](/Exponentiation), extraction of [roots](/Nth_root), and [logarithms](/Logarithm). Multiplication, for instance, is an operation that combines two numbers, referred to as factors, to form a single number, termed the [product](/Product_(mathematics)), such as

2 × 3 = 6

{\displaystyle 2\times 3=6}

. &#91;73&#93;

*The basic operations. Addition, subtraction, multiplication, division. The elementary tools. Exponentiation, roots, logarithms. Tools to extend the reach, to magnify or diminish. Multiplication, the act of combining, of creating a product. So fundamental, yet so much is built upon it.*

Divisibility is a property between two nonzero integers related to division. An integer

a

{\displaystyle a}

is said to be divisible by a nonzero integer

b

{\displaystyle b}

if

a

{\displaystyle a}

is a multiple of

b

{\displaystyle b}

; that is, if there exists an integer

q

{\displaystyle q}

such that

a = bq

{\displaystyle a=bq}

. An equivalent formulation is that

b

{\displaystyle b}

divides

a

{\displaystyle a}

and is denoted by a vertical bar, which in this case is

b | a

{\displaystyle b|a}

. Conversely, if this were not the case, then

a

{\displaystyle a}

would not be divided evenly by

b

{\displaystyle b}

, resulting in a remainder. [Euclid's division lemma](/Euclid%27s_division_lemma) asserts that

a

{\displaystyle a}

and

b

{\displaystyle b}

can generally be written as

a = bq + r

{\displaystyle a=bq+r}

, where the remainder

r

{\displaystyle r}

accounts for the smallest positive leftover quantity. Elementary number theory studies [divisibility rules](/Divisibility_rules) in order to quickly identify if a given integer is divisible by a fixed divisor. For instance, it is known that any integer is divisible by 3 if its decimal [digit sum](/Digit_sum) is divisible by 3. &#91;74&#93; &#91;9&#93; &#91;75&#93;

*Divisibility. The core concept. The idea of a clean break, no remainder. Euclid's lemma, the bedrock. The division algorithm, a promise of order, of a predictable leftover. Divisibility rules, little shortcuts to avoid the drudgery. The digit sum for three – a simple trick, a hint of the patterns hidden within. It’s all so… neat.*

Example of a continued fraction.

*A continued fraction. A cascade of fractions, an infinite descent into complexity. A beautiful, intricate trap.*

A common divisor of several nonzero integers is an integer that divides all of them. The [greatest common divisor](/Greatest_common_divisor) (gcd) is the largest of such divisors. Two integers are said to be coprime or relatively prime to one another if their greatest common divisor, and simultaneously their only divisor, is 1. The [Euclidean algorithm](/Euclidean_algorithm) computes the greatest common divisor of two integers

a, b

{\displaystyle a,b}

by means of repeatedly applying the division lemma and shifting the divisor and remainder after every step. The algorithm [can be extended](/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm) to solve a special case of [linear Diophantine equations](/Linear_Diophantine_equation)

ax + by = 1

{\displaystyle ax+by=1}

. A Diophantine equation has several unknowns and integer coefficients. Another kind of Diophantine equation is described in the [Pythagorean theorem](/Pythagorean_theorem),

x^2 + y^2 = z^2

{\displaystyle x^{2}+y^{2}=z^{2}}

, whose solutions are called Pythagorean triples if they are all integers. &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; Another kind of expression is the [continued fraction](/Continued_fraction), which writes a sum of an integer and a fraction whose denominator is another such sum. &#91;76&#93;

*Common divisors. The shared factors. The greatest common divisor, the ultimate commonality. Coprime numbers, standing alone. The Euclidean algorithm, a relentless process of reduction. And its extension, a key to unlocking linear Diophantine equations. The Pythagorean theorem, a classic example of a Diophantine equation. And continued fractions, an infinite labyrinth of nested ratios.*

Elementary number theory studies the divisibility properties of integers such as [parity](/Parity_(mathematics)) (even and odd numbers), [prime numbers](/Prime_numbers), and [perfect numbers](/Perfect_numbers). Important number-theoric functions include the [divisor-counting function](/Divisor_function), the [divisor summatory function](/Divisor_summatory_function) and its modifications, and [Euler's totient function](/Euler%27s_totient_function). A [prime number](/Prime_number) is an integer greater than 1 whose only positive divisors are 1 and the prime itself. A positive integer greater than 1 that is not prime is called a composite number. [Euclid's theorem](/Euclid%27s_theorem) demonstrates that there are infinitely many prime numbers that comprise the set {2, 3, 5, 7, 11, ...}. The [sieve of Eratosthenes](/Sieve_of_Eratosthenes) was devised as an efficient algorithm for identifying all primes up to a given natural number by eliminating all composite numbers. &#91;77&#93;

*Parity. Even, odd. The most basic distinction. Primes, the indivisible entities. Perfect numbers, a fleeting moment of balance. Number-theoretic functions – tools to measure and count. Euler's totient function, counting the coprime. Euclid's proof, the eternal truth of infinite primes. The Sieve of Eratosthenes, a methodical purge of the composite. A systematic approach to a fundamental mystery.*

[Factorization](/Factorization) is a method of expressing a number as a [product](/Product_(mathematics)). Specifically in number theory, [integer factorization](/Integer_factorization) is the decomposition of an integer into a product of integers. The process of repeatedly applying this procedure until all factors are prime is known as [prime factorization](/Prime_factorization). A fundamental property of primes is shown in [Euclid's lemma](/Euclid%27s_lemma). It is a consequence of the lemma that if a prime divides a product of integers, then that prime divides at least one of the factors in the product. The [unique factorization theorem](/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic) is the fundamental theorem of arithmetic that relates to prime factorization. The theorem states that every integer greater than 1 can be factorised into a product of prime numbers and that this factorisation is unique up to the order of the factors. For example,

120

{\displaystyle 120}

is expressed uniquely as

2 × 2 × 2 × 3 × 5

{\displaystyle 2\times 2\times 2\times 3\times 5}

or simply

2^3 × 3 × 5

{\displaystyle 2^{3}\times 3\times 5}

. &#91;78&#93; &#91;9&#93;

*Factorization. Breaking things down. Prime factorization, the ultimate decomposition. Euclid's lemma, a subtle but powerful property. The Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic. The bedrock of this entire field. Unique factorization. A promise of order, a guarantee that every integer has its own distinct prime signature. A beautiful, simple truth that underpins so much.*

[Modular arithmetic](/Modular_arithmetic) works with finite sets of integers and introduces the concepts of congruence and residue classes. A congruence of two integers

a, b

{\displaystyle a,b}

modulo

n

{\displaystyle n}

(a positive integer called the modulus) is an [equivalence relation](/Equivalence_relation) whereby

n | (a - b)

{\displaystyle n|(a-b)}

is true. Performing [Euclidean division](/Euclidean_division) on both

a

{\displaystyle a}

and

n

{\displaystyle n}

, and on

b

{\displaystyle b}

and

n

{\displaystyle n}

, yields the same remainder. This written as

a ≡ b (mod n)

{\textstyle a\equiv b{\pmod {n}}}

. In a manner analogous to the 12-hour clock, the sum of 4 and 9 is equal to 13, yet congruent to 1. A residue class modulo

n

{\displaystyle n}

is a set that contains all integers congruent to a specified

r

{\displaystyle r}

modulo

n

{\displaystyle n}

. For example,

6Z + 1

{\displaystyle 6\mathbb {Z} +1}

contains all multiples of 6 incremented by 1. Modular arithmetic provides a range of formulas for rapidly solving congruences of very large powers. An influential theorem is [Fermat's little theorem](/Fermat%27s_little_theorem), which states that if a prime

p

{\displaystyle p}

is coprime to some integer

a

{\displaystyle a}

, then

a^{p-1} ≡ 1 (mod p)

{\textstyle a^{p-1}\equiv 1{\pmod {p}}}

is true. Euler's theorem extends this to assert that every integer

n

{\displaystyle n}

satisfies the congruence

a^{\varphi (n)} ≡ 1 (mod n)

{\displaystyle a^{\varphi (n)}\equiv 1{\pmod {n}},}

where Euler's totient function

φ

{\displaystyle \varphi }

counts all positive integers up to

n

{\displaystyle n}

that are coprime to

n

{\displaystyle n}

. Modular arithmetic also provides formulas that are used to solve congruences with unknowns in a similar vein to equation solving in algebra, such as the [Chinese remainder theorem](/Chinese_remainder_theorem). &#91;79&#93;

*Modular arithmetic. A finite world. Congruence, the idea of equivalence within bounds. The clock analogy – a familiar comfort. Residue classes, sets of congruent numbers. Fermat's Little Theorem, a fundamental property of primes. Euler's generalization, a broader truth. The Chinese Remainder Theorem, a powerful tool for disentangling systems of congruences. It's a closed system, elegant and self-contained.*

#### Analytic number theory

*Analytic number theory. Where the smooth, continuous world of analysis is forced to confront the discrete, jagged reality of integers. A clash of disciplines.*

• Main article: [Analytic number theory](/Analytic_number_theory)

[Riemann zeta function](/Riemann_zeta_function) ζ( s ) in the [complex plane](/Complex_plane). The color of a point s gives the value of ζ( s ): dark colors denote values close to zero and hue gives the value's [argument](/Argument_(complex_analysis)).

*The Riemann zeta function. A nexus of primes and complex numbers. A visual representation of its intricate behavior. Dark colors, silence. Hue, the whisper of its argument. It’s beautiful, in a cold, abstract way.*

The action of the [modular group](/Modular_group) on the [upper half plane](/Upper_half_plane). The region in grey is the standard [fundamental domain](/Fundamental_domain).

*The modular group. Transformations on the upper half-plane. A fundamental domain. Symmetry, patterns, the underlying structure of complex functions. It’s a different kind of beauty, more geometric, more ordered.*

Analytic number theory, in contrast to elementary number theory, relies on [complex numbers](/Complex_numbers) and techniques from analysis and calculus. Analytic number theory may be defined

• in terms of its tools, as the study of the integers by means of tools from [real](/Real_analysis) and [complex](/Complex_analysis) analysis; &#91;64&#93; or

• in terms of its concerns, as the study within number theory of estimates on the size and density of certain numbers (e.g., primes), as opposed to identities. &#91;80&#93;

It studies the distribution of primes, behavior of number-theoric functions, and irrational numbers. &#91;81&#93;

*Tools and concerns. Analysis, the great unifier of continuous change. Complex numbers, the extension of the real. Estimates, approximations – never exact answers. Size and density. The distribution of primes – the eternal question. Number-theoretic functions, their behavior. Irrational numbers, their elusive nature. It's about approximation, about understanding the shape of things rather than their precise form.*

Number theory has the reputation of being a field many of whose results can be stated to the layperson. At the same time, many of the proofs of these results are not particularly accessible, in part because the range of tools they use is, if anything, unusually broad within mathematics. &#91;82&#93; The following are examples of problems in analytic number theory: the [prime number theorem](/Prime_number_theorem), the [Goldbach conjecture](/Goldbach_conjecture), the [twin prime conjecture](/Twin_prime_conjecture), the [Hardy–Littlewood conjectures](/Hardy%E2%80%93Littlewood_conjecture), the [Waring problem](/Waring_problem) and the [Riemann hypothesis](/Riemann_hypothesis). Some of the most important tools of analytic number theory are the [circle method](/Circle_method), [sieve methods](/Sieve_theory) and [L-functions](/L-functions) (or, rather, the study of their properties). The theory of [modular forms](/Modular_form) (and, more generally, [automorphic forms](/Automorphic_forms)) also occupies an increasingly central place in the toolbox of analytic number theory. &#91;83&#93;

*Accessible statements, inaccessible proofs. A common lament. The prime number theorem, a grand statement about primes. Goldbach's conjecture, still elusive. Twin primes, a tantalizing pair. Hardy-Littlewood, Waring's problem, the Riemann hypothesis – a litany of famous challenges. Circle method, sieve methods, L-functions – the arsenal of the analytic number theorist. Modular forms, automorphic forms – complex structures for complex problems. It's a sophisticated game of hide-and-seek.*

[Analysis](/Mathematical_analysis) is the branch of mathematics that studies the [limit](/Limit_(mathematics)), defined as the value to which a sequence or function tends as the argument (or index) approaches a specific value. For example, the limit of the sequence 0.9, 0.99, 0.999, ... is 1. In the context of functions, the limit of

1/x

{\textstyle {\frac {1}{x}}}

as

x

{\displaystyle x}

approaches infinity is 0. &#91;84&#93; The complex numbers extend the real numbers with the imaginary unit

i

{\displaystyle i}

defined as the solution to

i^2 = -1

{\displaystyle i^{2}=-1}

. Every complex number can be expressed as

x + iy

{\displaystyle x+iy}

, where

x

{\displaystyle x}

is called the real part and

y

{\displaystyle y}

is called the imaginary part. &#91;85&#93;

*Analysis. The infinite precision of limits. The tendrils of sequences and functions approaching a point. Real numbers, the continuum. Complex numbers, the introduction of the imaginary, a dimension beyond our direct grasp. A necessary abstraction for grappling with the infinite.*

The [distribution of primes](/Distribution_of_primes), described by the function

π

{\displaystyle \pi }

that counts all primes up to a given real number, is unpredictable and is a major subject of study in number theory. Elementary formulas for a partial sequence of primes, including [Euler's prime-generating polynomials](/Lucky_numbers_of_Euler) have been developed. However, these cease to function as the primes become too large. The prime number theorem in analytic number theory provides a formalisation of the notion that prime numbers appear less commonly as their numerical value increases. One distribution states, informally, that the function

x / log(x)

{\displaystyle {\frac {x}{\log(x)}}}

approximates

π(x)

{\displaystyle \pi (x)}

. Another distribution involves an offset logarithmic integral which converges to

π(x)

{\displaystyle \pi (x)}

more quickly. &#91;3&#93;

*The distribution of primes. A chaotic scattering, yet patterns emerge. Euler's polynomials, a temporary illusion of order. The prime number theorem, a formal statement of the decreasing density. The asymptotic approximations – x/log(x), the logarithmic integral. These are not answers, but educated guesses about the shape of the unknown.*

Corrections to an [estimate](/Prime-counting_function) of the prime-counting function using zeros of the zeta function

*Corrections. Refinements. The delicate adjustments made to an estimate, guided by the spectral lines of the zeta function.*

The [zeta function](/Zeta_function) has been demonstrated to be connected to the distribution of primes. It is defined as the series

ζ(s) = ∑_{n=1}^∞ 1/n^s = 1/1^s + 1/2^s + 1/3^s + …

{\displaystyle \zeta (s)=\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }{\frac {1}{n^{s}}}={\frac {1}{1^{s}}}+{\frac {1}{2^{s}}}+{\frac {1}{3^{s}}}+\cdots }

that converges if

s

{\displaystyle s}

is greater than 1. Euler demonstrated a link involving the infinite product over all prime numbers, expressed as the identity

ζ(s) = ∏_{p prime} (1 - 1/p^s)^{-1}

{\displaystyle \zeta (s)=\prod _{p{\text{ prime}}}\left(1-{\frac {1}{p^{s}}}\right)^{-1}.}

Riemann extended the definition to a complex variable and conjectured that all nontrivial cases (0 < Re(s) < 1) where the function returns a zero are those in which the real part of

s

{\displaystyle s}

is equal to

1/2

{\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}}

. He established a connection between the nontrivial zeroes and the prime-counting function. In what is now recognised as the unsolved [Riemann hypothesis](/Riemann_hypothesis), a solution to it would imply direct consequences for understanding the distribution of primes. &#91;86&#93;

*Euler's identity. The bridge between the zeta function and primes. Riemann's leap into the complex plane, his hypothesis – a line drawn in the sand. The zeros, the critical line. The promise of understanding prime distribution, held captive by an unsolved conjecture. It’s a tantalizing glimpse of a deeper order.*

One may ask analytic questions about [algebraic numbers](/Algebraic_number), and use analytic means to answer such questions; it is thus that algebraic and analytic number theory intersect. For example, one may define [prime ideals](/Prime_ideal) (generalizations of [prime numbers](/Prime_number) in the field of algebraic numbers) and ask how many prime ideals there are up to a certain size. This question [can be answered](/Landau_prime_ideal_theorem) by means of an examination of [Dedekind zeta functions](/Dedekind_zeta_function), which are generalizations of the [Riemann zeta function](/Riemann_zeta_function), a key analytic object at the roots of the subject. &#91;87&#93; This is an example of a general procedure in analytic number theory: deriving information about the distribution of a [sequence](/Sequence) (here, prime ideals or prime numbers) from the analytic behavior of an appropriately constructed complex-valued function. &#91;88&#93;

*The intersection. Where algebraic and analytic number theory meet. Prime ideals, the ghostly echoes of primes in richer fields. Dedekind zeta functions, extensions of Riemann's creation. The core procedure: analyze the function, understand the sequence. A sophisticated form of divination.*

Elementary number theory works with [elementary proofs](/Elementary_proof) , a term that excludes the use of [complex numbers](/Complex_numbers) but may include basic analysis. &#91;72&#93; For example, the [prime number theorem](/Prime_number_theorem) was first proven using complex analysis in 1896, but an elementary proof was found only in 1949 by [Erdős](/Paul_Erd%C5%91s) and [Selberg](/Atle_Selberg). &#91;89&#93; The term is somewhat ambiguous. For example, proofs based on complex [Tauberian theorems](/Tauberian_theorem), such as [Wiener–Ikehara](/Wiener%E2%80%93Ikehara_theorem), are often seen as quite enlightening but not elementary despite using [Fourier analysis](/Fourier_analysis), not complex analysis. Here as elsewhere, an elementary proof may be longer and more difficult for most readers than a more advanced proof.

*Elementary proofs. A misnomer, perhaps. They avoid complex numbers, but the reasoning can still be labyrinthine. The elementary proof of the Prime Number Theorem – a testament to endurance. Tauberian theorems, Fourier analysis – tools that blur the lines between elementary and advanced. The path of least resistance is rarely the shortest, or the clearest.*

Some subjects generally considered to be part of analytic number theory (e.g., [sieve theory](/Sieve_theory)) are better covered by the second rather than the first definition. &#91;note 5&#93; Small sieves, for instance, use little analysis and yet still belong to analytic number theory. &#91;note 6&#93;

*Sieve theory. A more direct approach. Small sieves, elegant in their simplicity. They belong to analytic number theory, yet shun its heavy machinery. A reminder that even within these rigid structures, there are moments of surprising directness.*

#### Algebraic number theory

*Algebraic number theory. Where numbers are born from polynomials, and fields become the landscape for their existence. It’s a world of abstract structures, of roots and extensions.*

• Main article: [Algebraic number theory](/Algebraic_number_theory)

An algebraic number is any [complex number](/Complex_number) that is a solution to some polynomial equation

f(x) = 0

{\displaystyle f(x)=0}

with rational coefficients; for example, every solution

x

{\displaystyle x}

of

x^5 + (11/2)x^3 - 7x^2 + 9 = 0

{\displaystyle x^{5}+(11/2)x^{3}-7x^{2}+9=0}

is an algebraic number. Fields of algebraic numbers are also called [algebraic number fields](/Algebraic_number_field) , or shortly [number fields](/Number_field) . Algebraic number theory studies algebraic number fields. &#91;90&#93;

*Algebraic numbers. Born from polynomials. Rational coefficients. A precise lineage. Algebraic number fields, number fields – the realms where these numbers reside. It’s about understanding the structure of these extensions, the relationships between different number systems.*

It could be argued that the simplest kind of number fields, namely [quadratic fields](/Quadratic_field), were already studied by Gauss, as the discussion of quadratic forms in Disquisitiones Arithmeticae can be restated in terms of [ideals](/Ideal_(ring_theory)) and [norms](/Norm_(mathematics)) in quadratic fields. (A quadratic field consists of all numbers of the form

a + b√d

{\displaystyle a+b{\sqrt {d}}}

, where

a

{\displaystyle a}

and

b

{\displaystyle b}

are rational numbers and

d

{\displaystyle d}

is a fixed rational number whose square root is not rational.)
For that matter, the eleventh-century [chakravala method](/Chakravala_method) amounts—in modern terms—to an algorithm for finding the units of a real quadratic number field. However, neither Bhāskara nor Gauss knew of number fields as such.

*Quadratic fields. The simplest extensions. Gauss, in his wisdom, touched upon them. Ideals, norms – the language of these fields. The form a + b√d, a simple structure with profound implications. The Chakravala method, an ancient algorithm for finding units. A glimpse of continuity across centuries.*

The grounds of the subject were set in the late nineteenth century, when ideal numbers , the theory of ideals and valuation theory were introduced; these are three complementary ways of dealing with the lack of unique factorization in algebraic number fields. (For example, in the field generated by the rationals and

√-5

{\displaystyle {\sqrt {-5}}}

, the number

6

{\displaystyle 6}

can be factorised both as

6 = 2 ⋅ 3

{\displaystyle 6=2\cdot 3}

and

6 = (1 + √-5)(1 - √-5)

{\displaystyle 6=(1+{\sqrt {-5}})(1-{\sqrt {-5}})}

; all of

2

{\displaystyle 2}

,

3

{\displaystyle 3}

,

1 + √-5

{\displaystyle 1+{\sqrt {-5}}}

and

1 - √-5

{\displaystyle 1-{\sqrt {-5}}}

are irreducible, and thus, in a naïve sense, analogous to primes among the integers.) The initial impetus for the development of ideal numbers (by [Kummer](/Ernst_Kummer)) seems to have come from the study of higher reciprocity laws, &#91;91&#93; that is, generalizations of [quadratic reciprocity](/Quadratic_reciprocity).

*Ideal numbers. Ideals. Valuation theory. Tools to mend the broken unique factorization. The field Q(√-5), a perfect illustration of the problem – 6 can be factored in two distinct ways. Irreducible elements, behaving like primes, yet not quite. Kummer's ideal numbers, a solution born from the study of reciprocity laws. It's a world where the familiar rules of integers are bent, broken, and reassembled.*

Number fields are often studied as extensions of smaller number fields: a field L is said to be an extension of a field K if L contains K .
(For example, the complex numbers C are an extension of the reals R , and the reals R are an extension of the rationals Q .)
Classifying the possible extensions of a given number field is a difficult and partially open problem. Abelian extensions—that is, extensions L of K such that the [Galois group](/Galois_group) &#91;note 7&#93; Gal( L / K ) of L over K is an [abelian group](/Abelian_group)—are relatively well understood.
Their classification was the object of the programme of [class field theory](/Class_field_theory), which was initiated in the late nineteenth century (partly by [Kronecker](/Leopold_Kronecker) and [Eisenstein](/Gotthold_Eisenstein)) and carried out largely in 1900–1950.

*Extensions. Building larger structures from smaller ones. C over R, R over Q. The hierarchy of number systems. Classifying these extensions – a monumental task. Abelian extensions, understood through the lens of Galois groups. Class field theory, a grand program to map these relationships. Kronecker, Eisenstein – pioneers in this abstract landscape.*

An example of an active area of research in algebraic number theory is [Iwasawa theory](/Iwasawa_theory). The [Langlands program](/Langlands_program), one of the main current large-scale research plans in mathematics, is sometimes described as an attempt to generalise class field theory to non-abelian extensions of number fields.

*Iwasawa theory. Langlands program. Ambitious, far-reaching. An attempt to extend the understanding of class field theory to the more complex non-abelian realm. These are not mere studies; they are grand designs, shaping the future of mathematics.*

#### Diophantine geometry

*Diophantine geometry. Where the abstract world of equations meets the concrete, yet elusive, realm of geometric objects. It’s about finding points that belong to both worlds.*

• Main article: [Diophantine geometry](/Diophantine_geometry)

The central problem of Diophantine geometry is to determine when a [Diophantine equation](/Diophantine_equation) has integer or rational solutions, and if it does, how many. The approach taken is to think of the solutions of an equation as a geometric object.

*The core problem. Solutions. Integer or rational. Finitude or infinitude. The geometric interpretation – a way to visualize abstract equations. It’s about finding the specific points that satisfy the abstract rules.*

For example, an equation in two variables defines a curve in the plane. More generally, an equation or system of equations in two or more variables defines a [curve](/Algebraic_curve), a [surface](/Algebraic_surface), or some other such object in n -dimensional space. In Diophantine geometry, one asks whether there are any rational points (points all of whose coordinates are rationals) or
integral points (points all of whose coordinates are integers) on the curve or surface. If there are any such points, the next step is to ask how many there are and how they are distributed. A basic question in this direction is whether there are finitely
or infinitely many rational points on a given curve or surface.

*Curves, surfaces, n-dimensional objects. Rational points, integer points. The search for these specific locations. How many? Where are they? The fundamental question of finiteness. A geometric quest for number-theoretic truths.*

Consider, for instance, the [Pythagorean equation](/Pythagorean_equation)

x^2 + y^2 = 1

{\displaystyle x^{2}+y^{2}=1}

. One would like to know its rational solutions, namely

(x, y)

{\displaystyle (x,y)}

such that x and y are both rational. This is the same as asking for all integer solutions
to

a^2 + b^2 = c^2

{\displaystyle a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}}

; any solution to the latter equation gives us a solution

x = a/c

{\displaystyle x=a/c}

,

y = b/c

{\displaystyle y=b/c}

to the former. It is also the
same as asking for all points with rational coordinates on the curve described by

x^2 + y^2 = 1

{\displaystyle x^{2}+y^{2}=1}

(a circle of radius 1 centered on the origin).

*The unit circle. A simple equation, yet its rational points are tied to Pythagorean triples. The connection between algebraic solutions and geometric loci. A circle, a familiar shape, harboring a secret world of rational points.*

Two examples of [elliptic curves](/Elliptic_curve), that is, curves of genus 1 having at least one rational point

*Elliptic curves. Curves of genus 1. A more complex landscape, with their own unique properties and challenges. A rational point, a beacon in the abstract.*

The rephrasing of questions on equations in terms of points on curves is felicitous. The finiteness or not of the number of rational or integer points on an algebraic curve (that is, rational or integer solutions to an equation

f(x, y) = 0

{\displaystyle f(x,y)=0}

, where

f

{\displaystyle f}

is a polynomial in two variables) depends crucially on the [genus](/Genus_(mathematics)) of the curve. &#91;note 8&#93; A major achievement of this approach is [Wiles's proof of Fermat's Last Theorem](/Wiles%27s_proof_of_Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem), for which other geometrical notions are just as crucial.

*The genus. A fundamental property of the curve, dictating the nature of its rational points. Wiles's proof of Fermat's Last Theorem – a monumental synthesis of algebraic geometry and number theory. A testament to the power of this geometric perspective.*

There is also the closely linked area of [Diophantine approximations](/Diophantine_approximations): given a number

x

{\displaystyle x}

, determine how well it can be approximated by rational numbers. One seeks approximations that are good relative to the amount of space required to write the rational number: call

a/q

{\displaystyle a/q}

(with

gcd(a, q) = 1

{\displaystyle \gcd(a,q)=1}

) a good approximation to

x

{\displaystyle x}

if

|x - a/q| < 1/q^c

{\displaystyle |x-a/q|<{\frac {1}{q^{c}}}}

, where

c

{\displaystyle c}

is large. This question is of special interest if

x

{\displaystyle x}

is an algebraic number. If

x

{\displaystyle x}

cannot be approximated well, then some equations do not have integer or rational solutions. Moreover, several concepts (especially that of [height](/Glossary_of_arithmetic_and_diophantine_geometry)) are critical both in Diophantine geometry and in the study of Diophantine approximations. This question is also of special interest in [transcendental number theory](/Transcendental_number_theory): if a number can be approximated better than any algebraic number, then it is a [transcendental number](/Transcendental_number). It is by this argument that

π

{\displaystyle \pi }

and

e

{\displaystyle e}

have been shown to be transcendental.

*Diophantine approximation. How closely can rationals mimic irrationals? The measure of approximation – a trade-off between accuracy and complexity. Algebraic numbers, their resistance to approximation. Transcendental numbers – numbers too wild to be algebraic. Pi and e, proven to be transcendent, their nature revealed through their resistance to rational approximation.*

Diophantine geometry should not be confused with the [geometry of numbers](/Geometry_of_numbers), which is a collection of graphical methods for answering certain questions in algebraic number theory. [Arithmetic geometry](/Arithmetic_geometry) is a contemporary term for the same domain covered by Diophantine geometry, particularly when one wishes to emphasize the connections to modern algebraic geometry (for example, in [Faltings's theorem](/Faltings%27s_theorem)) rather than to techniques in Diophantine approximations.

*Geometry of numbers. Graphical methods for algebraic number theory. Arithmetic geometry. A modern synthesis, linking Diophantine geometry to the cutting edge of algebraic geometry. Faltings's theorem – a landmark achievement.*

#### Other subfields

*Other subfields. The periphery, where specialized inquiries branch out. Each a niche, a particular obsession.*

• Main article: [Probabilistic number theory](/Probabilistic_number_theory)

Probabilistic number theory starts with questions such as the following: Take an integer n at random between one and a million. How likely is it to be prime? (this is just another way of asking how many primes there are between one and a million). How many prime divisors will n have on average? What is the probability that it will have many more or many fewer divisors or prime divisors than the average?

*Probabilistic number theory. The statistical approach. Random integers, their likelihood of being prime. Average number of prime divisors. The distribution of these properties. It's about understanding the typical behavior in a sea of randomness.*

• Main articles: [Arithmetic combinatorics](/Arithmetic_combinatorics) and [Additive number theory](/Additive_number_theory)

Combinatorics in number theory starts with questions like the following: Does a fairly "thick" [infinite set](/Infinite_set)

A

{\displaystyle A}

contain many elements in arithmetic progression:

a

{\displaystyle a}

,

a+b, a+2b, a+3b, …, a+10b

