*Arithmetic combinatorics. The structure within sets. Arithmetic progressions within dense sets. Additive number theory. Representing integers as sums. It's about finding order and structure in collections of numbers.*

• Main article: [Computational number theory](/Computational_number_theory)

A [Lehmer sieve](/Lehmer_sieve), a primitive [digital computer](/Digital_computer) used to find [primes](/Primes) and solve simple [Diophantine equations](/Diophantine_equations)

*Computational number theory. The mechanical approach. Algorithms. Lehmer sieve – an early attempt to automate the search. The question of efficiency. Can it be computed? Can it be computed *quickly*?*

There are two main questions: "Can this be computed?" and "Can it be computed rapidly?" Anyone can test whether a number is prime or, if it is not, split it into prime factors; doing so rapidly is another matter. Fast algorithms for [testing primality](/Primality_test) are now known, but, in spite of much work (both theoretical and practical), no truly fast algorithm for factoring.

*Primality testing, fast. Factoring, still elusive. The great asymmetry. The fundamental problem that underpins much of modern cryptography. The computational challenge that defines a generation of research.*

