### Applications

For a long time, number theory in general, and the study of prime numbers in particular, was seen as the canonical example of pure mathematics, with no applications outside of mathematics other than the use of prime numbered gear teeth to distribute wear evenly. &#91;92&#93; In particular, number theorists such as [British](/United_Kingdom) mathematician [G. H. Hardy](/G._H._Hardy) prided themselves on doing work that had absolutely no military significance. &#91;93&#93; The number-theorist [Leonard Dickson](/Leonard_Dickson) (1874–1954) said "Thank God that number theory is unsullied by any application". Such a view is no longer applicable to number theory. &#91;94&#93;

*Pure mathematics. The ivory tower. Hardy, with his disdain for utility. Dickson, thanking God for its lack of application. A quaint, almost innocent, perspective. A view shattered by the relentless march of progress.*

This vision of the purity of number theory was shattered in the 1970s, when it was publicly announced that prime numbers could be used as the basis for the creation of [public-key cryptography](/Public-key_cryptography) algorithms. &#91;95&#93; Schemes such as RSA are based on the difficulty of factoring large composite numbers into their prime factors. &#91;96&#93; These applications have led to significant study of [algorithms](/Algorithm) for computing with prime numbers, and in particular of [primality testing](/Primality_test), methods for determining whether a given number is prime. Prime numbers are also used in computing for [checksums](/Checksum), [hash tables](/Hash_table), and [pseudorandom number generators](/Pseudorandom_number_generator).

*Cryptography. Public-key systems. RSA. The difficulty of factoring – the bedrock of modern security. Primality testing, essential for generating secure keys. Checksums, hash tables, pseudorandom numbers – the subtle fingerprints of number theory in everyday computation. It’s a strange twist of fate, the abstract becoming the guardian of secrets.*

In 1974, [Donald Knuth](/Donald_Knuth) said "virtually every theorem in elementary number theory arises in a natural, motivated way in connection with the problem of making computers do high-speed numerical calculations". &#91;97&#93;
Elementary number theory is taught in [discrete mathematics](/Discrete_mathematics) courses for [computer scientists](/Computer_scientist). It also has applications to the continuous in [numerical analysis](/Numerical_analysis). &#91;98&#93;

*Knuth. A prophet of computational number theory. Elementary number theory, finding its purpose in the relentless demands of high-speed calculation. Discrete mathematics for computer scientists. Even its influence stretches to the continuous realm of numerical analysis.*

Number theory has now several modern applications spanning diverse areas such as:

• [Computer science](/Computer_science): The [fast Fourier transform](/Fast_Fourier_transform) (FFT) algorithm, which is used to efficiently compute the discrete Fourier transform, has important applications in signal processing and data analysis. &#91;99&#93;

• [Physics](/Physics): The [Riemann hypothesis](/Riemann_hypothesis) has connections to the distribution of prime numbers and has been studied for its potential implications in physics. &#91;100&#93;

• [Error correction codes](/Error_correction_code): The theory of finite fields and algebraic geometry have been used to construct efficient error-correcting codes. &#91;101&#93;

• Study of musical scales: the concept of "[equal temperament](/Equal_temperament)", which is the basis for most modern Western music, involves dividing the [octave](/Octave) into 12 equal parts. &#91;102&#93; This has been studied using number theory and in particular the properties of the 12th root of 2.

*Computer science. FFT. Signal processing. Physics. The Riemann Hypothesis, a whisper from the quantum realm. Error correction codes, the digital guardians of information. Music. Equal temperament, the mathematical harmony of sound. Number theory, it seems, has infiltrated everything.*

